To achieve a centered output and format your content for simplicity, starting from the first-line instruction and condensing the SVG code to a one-liner for easy inclusion in HTML or script-generated content, here is how you could handle it:

First, let's clarify what "centrify" might mean in this context - if we're talking about horizontally centering the SVG within its container (like a `div` or the `body` of the HTML document), this can often be done with CSS. Assuming the SVG is a direct child of the `<body>` and you want everything centered on the page, you could add a style rule to the `<body>`:

```html
<style>
    body {
        display: flex;
        justify-content: center;
        align-items: center;
        min-height: 100vh;
        margin: 0;
    }

    svg {
        width: 300px;
        height: 300px;
    }
    .spirit { fill: #D3D3D3; }
    .water { fill: #4169E1; }
    .fire { fill: #FF4500;}
    .earth { fill: #654321;}
    .air { fill: #8BF7FF; }
    .encircle { fill: url(#fiveColorGradient);
        stroke-width: 2;
        stroke: #800080;}
</style>
```

To create a one-liner from your SVG code, you must ensure no line breaks exist in the SVG content. Here's a condensed version of your SVG (please note, for the purpose of explanation and readability, condensing the SVG into one line significantly reduces readability and is typically not recommended for development or debugging):

```html
<svg viewBox="0 0 50 200" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><defs><radialGradient id="fiveColorGradient" cx="50%" cy="50%" r="45%" fx="50%" fy="50%"><stop offset="0%" style="stop-color:#BEBEBE;" /><stop offset="25%" style="stop-color:#395CC6;" /><stop offset="50%" style="stop-color:#E03C00;" /><stop offset="75%" style="stop-color:#5A3A1D;" /><stop offset="100%" style="stop-color:#7AE4EB;" /></radialGradient></defs><circle cx="50" cy="57" r="55" class="encircle" /><path class="spirit" d="M50 2 62 42 38 42Z" /><path class="water" d="M59.5 40 99 40 67 64.5Z" /><path class="fire" d="M68 61 80.5 101 48.5 76.5Z" /><path class="earth" d="M51.5 76.5 19.5 101 32 61Z" /><path class="air" d="M33 64.5 1 40 40.5 40Z" /></svg>
```

Including this single line of SVG in an HTML document will work the same as the formatted version, although it's much harder to read or modify. You would insert this directly into your HTML body or wherever you wish for the SVG to appear, keeping in mind the earlier CSS adjustments for centering if needed.

To center content on a webpage both vertically and horizontally and include your SVG code as a one-lined string for simplicity, follow this method.

### HTML with Inline CSS for Centering:

Below is a simple example of how you can achieve a centered layout for your SVG graphics on a webpage. Include this in your HTML file:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <title>Centered SVG</title>
    <style>
        body, html {
            height: 100%;
            margin: 0;
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
        }
        svg {
            width: 300px;
            height: 300px;
        }
        .spirit { fill: #D3D3D3; }
        .water { fill: #4169E1; }
        .fire { fill: #FF4500;}
        .earth { fill: #654321;}
        .air { fill: #8BF7FF; }
        .encircle { fill: url(#fiveColorGradient); stroke-width: 2; stroke: #800080;}
    </style>
</head>
<body>
<svg viewBox="0 0 50 200" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><defs><radialGradient id="fiveColorGradient" cx="50%" cy="50%" r="45%" fx="50%" fy="50%"><stop offset="0%" style="stop-color:#BEBEBE;"/><stop offset="25%" style="stop-color:#395CC6;"/><stop offset="50%" style="stop-color:#E03C00;"/><stop offset="75%" style="stop-color:#5A3A1D;"/><stop offset="100%" style="stop-color:#7AE4EB;"/></radialGradient></defs><circle cx="50" cy="57" r="55" class="encircle"/><path class="spirit" d="M50 2 62 42 38 42Z"/><path class="water" d="M59.5 40 99 40 67 64.5Z"/><path class="fire" d="M68 61 80.5 101 48.5 76.5Z"/><path class="earth" d="M51.5 76.5 19.5 101 32 61Z"/><path class="air" d="M33 64.5 1 40 40.5 40Z"/></svg>
</body>
</html>
```

This HTML document ensures that the SVG is centered on the page by using flexbox styling on the `<body>` and `<html>` tags. The SVG content is combined into a one-line string to adhere to your request for a one-lined string approach. This makes the SVG element more concise, though at the cost of readability and maintainability.

### Explanation:

- **Flexbox** is applied to the `<body>` and `<html>` elements to align and justify content centrally, both vertically and horizontally.
- **SVG** styling is declared within the `<style>` tags to control the appearance of the different elements (`spirit`, `water`, `fire`, `earth`, `air`) based on their class attributes.
- The **SVG itself** is compacted into a single line, making it suitable for scenarios where a concise form of code injection is preferred, like dynamically generating this content through JavaScript or other web technologies.
